\title{CASPEN: Celltype-Aware Stacked Pathway-Guided Ensemble Prediction}
\description{
CASPEN (celltype aware stacked pathway guided ensemble) trains and evaluates
celltype-aware pathway-guided ensemble models on high-dimensional omics data.
Supports binary, multi-class, and survival outcomes with pathway selection,
gene selection, celltype-aware pathway expansion, and stacked-generalization
meta-learning.
}
\section{Model backends}{

CASPEN uses short model abbreviations across functions. Use
\code{caspen_model_info()} to see the backend package for each abbreviation and
the installed package version on the current machine. Common abbreviations
include \code{XG} (xgboost), \code{RF} (random forest), \code{EN} (elastic net), \code{GB}
(gradient boosting), \code{KNN} (k-nearest neighbors), \code{SVM} (support vector
machine), \code{NB} (naive Bayes), \code{DCT} (decision tree), \code{NN} (neural network),
\code{ADB} (AdaBoost), and \code{MB} (model-based boosting).
}

\section{LLM and literature priors}{

CASPEN can use literature priors in three ways. First, users can supply
\code{literature.features} and \code{pathway.prior} directly. Second, CASPEN can score
pathway names by normalized PubMed counts or PubTator3 gene-annotation
evidence with \code{prior.method = "pubmed_count"} or \code{"pubtator"} in
\code{llm_literature_signatures()}, and \code{llm.prior.method = "pubmed_count"} or
\code{"pubtator"} in \code{pathway_select()}. These do not require an LLM key. Third,
CASPEN can query an LLM through the OpenAI API by setting
\code{OPENAI_API_KEY}, or through a local/custom function with \code{llm.provider = "custom"} and \code{llm.fn}. For a free local option, install Ollama, run
\verb{ollama pull qwen2.5:7b}, keep Ollama running, and pass an \code{llm.fn} wrapper
that calls \verb{http://localhost:11434/api/generate}.
}

